Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • A Markov chain is a dependent sequence of random variables X1,X2,X1,X2, or or random vectors X1,X2,X1,X2, having the property that the future is independent of the past given the present
  • Conditional distribution of Xn+1Xn+1 given X1,,XnX1,,Xn depends only on XnXn
  • The Markov chain has stationary transition probabilities if the conditional distribution of Xn+1Xn+1 given XnXn is the same for all nn
    • Every Markov chain used in MCMC has this property
  • The joint distribution of X1,,XnX1,,Xn is determined by the initial distribution of the Markov chain and the transition probabilities
    • Marginal distribution of X1X1
    • Conditional distribution of Xn+1Xn+1 given XnXn

Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • A scalar functional of a Markov chain is a time series, but not necessarily a Markov chain
  • A Markov chain is stationary if its initial distribution is stationary
    • Different from having stationary transition probabilities
    • All chains used in MCMC have stationary transition probabilities, but none are exactly stationary

Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • To be (exactly) stationary, must start the chain with simulation from the equilibrium (invariant, stationary) distribution
  • If chain is stationary, then every iterate XiXi has the same marginal distribution, which is the equilibrium distribution
  • If chain is not stationary but has a unique equilibrium distribution, which includes chains used in MCMC, then the marginal distribution XiXi converges to the equilibrium distribution as i→∞i→∞

Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • Let ππ be a probability distribution having support X⊆RdX⊆Rd, d≥1d≥1 we want to explore
  • When i.i.d. observations are unavailable, a Markov chain with stationary distribution ππ can be utilized
  • Summarize ππ with expectations, quantiles, density plots

Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • Suppose X1,,XnX1,,Xn are simulation from a Markov chain having a unique equilibrium distribution (say ππ), and suppose we want to know an expectation
    μg=E[g(Xi)]=∫Xg(x)π(dx)μg=E[g(Xi)]=∫Xg(x)π(dx)
    where the expectation is with respect to unique equilibrium distribution ππ
  • If Eπ|g(Xi)|<∞Eπ|g(Xi)|<∞, then
    μ^n=1n∑i=1ng(Xi)→a.s.μgas n→∞(SLLN).μ^n=1n∑i=1ng(Xi)→a.s.μgas n→∞(SLLN).

Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • The central limit theorem (CLT) for Markov chains says
    n−−√(μ^n−Eπg(Xi))→N(0,σ2),n(μ^n−Eπg(Xi))→N(0,σ2),
    where
    σ2=Varg(Xi)+2∑k=1∞Cov[g(Xi),g(Xi+k)]σ2=Varg(Xi)+2∑k=1∞Cov[g(Xi),g(Xi+k)]
  • CLT holds if Eπ|g(Xi)|2+ϵ<∞Eπ|g(Xi)|2+ϵ<∞ and the Markov chain is geometrically ergodic
  • Can estimate σ2σ2 in various ways
  • Verifying such a mixing condition is generally very challenging
  • Nevertheless, we expect the CLT to hold in practice when using a smart sampler

Batch means

  • In order to make MCMC practical, need a method to estimate the variance σ2σ2 in the CLT, then can proceed just like in OMC
  • If σ^2σ^2 is a consistent estimate of σ2σ2, then an asymptotic 95% confidence interval for μgμg is
    μ^n1.96σ^n−−√μ^n1.96σ^n
  • The method of batch means estimates the asymptotic variance for a stationary time series

Batch means

  • Markov chain CLT says
    μ^n≈N(μg,σ2n)μ^n≈N(μg,σ2n)
  • Suppose bb evenly divides nn and we have the means
    μ^b,k=1b∑i=bk+1bk+bg(Xi)μ^b,k=1b∑i=bk+1bk+bg(Xi)
    for k=1,,a=n/bk=1,,a=n/b
  • Then each of these batch means satisfies (if bb is sufficiently large)
    μ^b,k≈N(μg,σ2b)μ^b,k≈N(μg,σ2b)

Batch means

  • Thus empirical variance of the sequence of batch means
    1a∑k=1a(μ^b,k−μ^n)21a∑k=1a(μ^b,k−μ^n)2
    estimates σ2/bσ2/b
  • And b/nb/n times this estimates σ2/nσ2/n, the asymptotic variance of μ^nμ^n
  • Batch means can produce a strongly consistent estimator of σ2σ2 if b→∞b→∞ and a→∞a→∞ as n→∞n→∞

Stopping rules

  • Suppose ϵ>0ϵ>0, then a **fixed-width stopping rule* terminates the simulation the first time half-width (or width) of a confidence interval is sufficiently small
  • That is, simulate until
    1.96σ^n−−√<ϵ.1.96σ^n<ϵ.

Example: AR(1)

The following will provide an observation from the MC 1 step ahead

ar1 <- function(m, rho, tau) {
rho*m + rnorm(1, 0, tau)
}

Next, we add to this function so that we can give it a Markov chain and the result will be p observations from the Markov chain

ar1.gen <- function(mc, p, rho, tau, q=1) {
loc <- length(mc)
junk <- double(p)
mc <- append(mc, junk)

for(i in 1:p){
j <- i+loc-1
mc[(j+1)] <- ar1(mc[j], rho, tau)
}
return(mc)
}

Markov chain Monte Carlo

  • MCMC methods are used most often in Bayesian inference where the equilibrium (invariant, stationary) distribution is a posterior distribution
  • Challenge lies in construction of a suitable Markov chain with ff as its stationary distribution

  • A key problem is we only get to observe tt observations from {Xt}{Xt}, which are serially dependent

  • Other questions to consider
    • How good are my MCMC estimators?
    • How long to run my Markov chain simulation?
    • How to compare MCMC samplers?
    • What to do in high-dimensional settings?

Metropolis-Hastings algorithm

Setting X0=x0X0=x0 (somehow), the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm generates Xt+1Xt+1 given Xt=xtXt=xt as follows:

  1. Sample a candidate value X∗∼g(⋅|xt)X∗∼g(⋅|xt) where gg is the proposal distribution
  2. Compute the MH ratio R(xt,X∗)R(xt,X∗), where
    R(xt,X∗)=f(x∗)g(xt|x∗)f(xt)g(x∗|xt)R(xt,X∗)=f(x∗)g(xt|x∗)f(xt)g(x∗|xt)
  3. Set
    Xt+1={x∗ w.p.\ min{R(xt,X∗),1}xt otherwiseXt+1={x∗ w.p.\ min{R(xt,X∗),1}xt otherwise

Metropolis-Hastings algorithm

  • Irreducibility and aperiodicity depend on the choice of gg, these must be checked
  • Performance (finite sample) depends on the choice of gg also, be careful

Independence chains

  • Suppose g(x∗|xt)=g(x∗)g(x∗|xt)=g(x∗), this yields an independence chain since the proposal does not depend on the current state

  • In this case, the MH ratio is

    R(xt,X∗)=f(x∗)g(xt)f(xt)g(x∗),R(xt,X∗)=f(x∗)g(xt)f(xt)g(x∗),
    and the resulting Markov chain will be irreducible and aperiodic if g>0g>0 where f>0f>0

  • A good envelope function gg should resemble ff, but should cover ff in the tails

Random walk chains

  • Generate X∗X∗ such that ϵ∼h(⋅)ϵ∼h(⋅) and set X∗=Xt+ϵX∗=Xt+ϵ, then g(x∗|xt)=h(x∗−xt)g(x∗|xt)=h(x∗−xt)

  • Common choices of h(⋅)h(⋅) are symmetric zero mean random variables with a scale parameter, e.g. a Uniform(−a,a−a,a), Normal(0,σ20,σ2), c∗Tν,c∗Tν,

  • For symmetric zero mean random variables, the MH ratio is
    R(xt,X∗)=f(x∗)f(xt)R(xt,X∗)=f(x∗)f(xt)

  • If the support of ff is connected and hh is positive in a neighborhood of 0, then the chain is irreducible and aperiodic.

Example: Markov chain basics

Independence Metropolis sampler with Exp(θθ) proposal

ind.chain <- function(x, n, theta = 1) {
  ## if theta = 1, then this is an iid sampler
  m <- length(x)
  x <- append(x, double(n))
  for(i in (m+1):length(x)){
    x.prime <- rexp(1, rate=theta)
    u <- exp((x[(i-1)]-x.prime)*(1-theta))
    if(runif(1) < u)
      x[i] <- x.prime
    else
      x[i] <- x[(i-1)]
  }
  return(x)
}

Example: Markov chain basics

Random Walk Metropolis sampler with N(0,σ0,σ) proposal

rw.chain <- function(x, n, sigma = 1) {
  m <- length(x)
  x <- append(x, double(n))
  for(i in (m+1):length(x)){
    x.prime <- x[(i-1)] + rnorm(1, sd = sigma)
    u <- exp((x[(i-1)]-x.prime))
    u
    if(runif(1) < u && x.prime > 0)
      x[i] <- x.prime
    else
      x[i] <- x[(i-1)]
  }
  return(x)
}
